<br>
You already know about towns being used as both places for shops and almost as &quot;countries&quot; (users controlling areas will appear in the moderator column as forum hosts), so perhaps the most important information now would be how the character stat and customization system is set up.  Each user can create one or more characters to use (just one at a time that that is actually used for battle, others can be shopkeepers, etc.).  After a character has been chosen, they will select a class from the current class level they have.  The classes and levels are as follows:<br>
<br>
Level 1<br>
<br>
-Squire<br>
-Chemist<br>
<br>
Level 2<br>
<br>
-Knight<br>
-Archer<br>
-Priest<br>
-Wizard<br>
<br>
Level 3<br>
<br>
-Monk<br>
-Thief<br>
-Oracle<br>
-Time mage<br>
<br>
Level 4<br>
<br>
-Geomancer<br>
-Lancer<br>
-Mediator<br>
-Summoner<br>
<br>
Level 5<br>
<br>
-Samurai<br>
-Ninja<br>
-Calculator<br>
-Dancer<br>
-Bard<br>
-Mime<br>
<br>
Level 6<br>
<br>
-Custom class with one special ability that has to be okay'd<br>
<br>
(If you would like additional info on the classes, visit this site: <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.ffgurus.net/fft/jobs/lvl1.shtml">www.ffgurus.net/fft/jobs/lvl1.shtml</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> )<br>
<br>
Each class has its own unique abilities which can be set.  I will set the abilities for level 1 and maybe level 2 tomorrow and for other levels as people get there.  Also, each class has a specific stat boost from the default stats which are as follows:<br>
<br>
HP: 100<br>
AP: 10<br>
STR: 10<br>
DEF: 10<br>
M-POW: 10<br>
M-DEF: 10<br>
<br>
To gain classes and class levels, you must participate in and win battles.  Upon winning a battle, you gain all abilities of the class you are in for later use even when you aren't that class.  You also gain money (the amount depends on the level of defeated foe) and you gain a stat level (even if you don't win, all you have to do is participate).  Once you have won one battle as a level one class, you will unlock level two classes.  You must win two battles as a level two class to move to level three, 2 as level three to move to level four, three as a level four class to move to level five, and 3 as a level five class to move to level 6.  Alternately, if you lose two straight battles as a class, it will count as a battle won as that class, making it easier for people to come in later when others are already high classes.<br>
<br>
An explanation on stat levels (just level for short):  <br>
Stat levels allow you to increase a stat of your character.  Each stat level you have means you can raise one stat by one, or ten if it is HP.<br>
<br>
An explanation of stats:<br>
<br>
HP is obvious<br>
AP is ability points (similar to mp, consumed to use abilities)<br>
STR is base physical attack<br>
DEF is defense (divide by two to find damage blocked)<br>
M-POW is base magic attack<br>
M-DEF is magic defense (divide by two to find damage blocked)<br>
<br>
Abilities:<br>
<br>
Each character can set three abilities and a limit break that is used once per battle with 5% or less of hp left.  The other three abilities can be set if you are the class that it is from, or if you win a battle with a class that has that ability.<br>
<br>
Money/Items:<br>
<br>
Money after battle is level 100 gil if you win a battle with a level 0 foe.  After that, you just add 50 to that amount to find gil won.  A loser gains 1/4 of what would have been earned, had they won, just to give people a chance.   Items will be used as items, not too complicated.  A list of items will be compiled soon, contribute suggestions for items in the suggestions forum.  Also, weapons, shields/headgear, armor and accessories can be equipped to boost stats.  To begin with, each character has a low level weapon that fits their class and doesn't boost stats, but weapons that do boost stats can be purchased.<br>
<br>
How a battle works:<br>
<br>
In a specified area (probably &quot;neutral&quot; areas like forests that I will create, or even on the land of countries ex: Bethla Garrison.  Basically anywhere except trade cities), users can use their characters to battle eachother.  You can battle for control of areas (see below) or you can just battle to battle.  The lower level user attacks first, if the levels are the same, just work it out.  Using attacks and abilities (the abilities will have added effects, which last until an item or ability that can cure that ailment is used, and/or boosted attack or defense for one turn).  The attack is calculated by adding any strength added by an ability and the base attack and then the defense is subtracted from that (divide the def by two).  Any attack remaining is subtracted from HP.  When no HP remains, you're dead.  AP are used in battle to execute abilities.  When you run out, you can no longer use abilities.  And finally, limit breaks.  They can be used once per battle when hp is at 5% or below.  Users will create their own limit breaks that are FAIR.  A good strategy would be to keep your foe's HP above 5% until you can defeat him/her in one blow.<br>
<br>
More info on controlling areas:<br>
<br>
When you begin, you need to select a country to be placed in.  If already occupied, you must ask leaders of that area to be allowed to become part of that country.  As countries gain control of another area of land, they will become an empire and need to name their empire and place in the hall of records to which empire they belong or if they may just put 'independant'.  You may not just take over an empty country, it must be in use first, but you may leave a country and enter another.  This way, just b/c you were the first to use the RPG battle section, you can't just take everything over.  To acquire a country through conquest, you must challenge that country to a battle.  One of the characters from each country will battle for control.  Whoever loses must relinquish control of that country and either become part of the other empire, or leave the area.  Also, you can rebel and take over an empire through revolution, just challenge the leader.  Whoever wins has the choice of whether the loser must go or can say.  I know this is confusing, so if you have questions, just ask.<br>
<br>
Merchant shops:<br>
<br>
You can have a separate identity that runs a shop.  Basically, what you do is create unique weapons to sell that have realistic abilities and added effects and you sell them, along with items.  That's about it, except that you make a shop only in trade cities (Dorter Trade City, for example).<br>
<br>
If you have any questions or I haven't covered something, post a reply about it.  If you have any suggestions, post them in the suggestions forum, that's what it is there for.  <br>
<br>
Added note:  Stats and character bios can be posted in the hall of records, which I am about to create.<br>
